ce:section.ce:para:
CA-CQDs presented excellent tracing ability in the flow experiment. The relationship curve of the accumulation, relative concentration of the tracer and injection volume was obtained according to the measurement of the produced fluid at different stages during the flow experiment (Fig. 7c and d). CA-CQDs demonstrated a similar breakthrough–elution process and higher accumulation and maximum relative concentration compared with the NaCl tracer. Therefore, the adsorption of CA-CQDs in pores was low and the transport capacity of CA-CQDs was strong. In addition, it was found that CA-CQDs in the 43.3 × 10−3 μm2 sand-filled pipe began to break through near the cumulative injection of 1 PV, and the stable pressure after the injection of CA-CQDs was 0.243 MPa (Table 6
                        ), which was almost the same as the water flooding stable pressure. This indicated that the adsorption of CA-CQDs was small likely due to the repulsion between acidic groups of CA-CQDs and negatively charged silica sand surface. At the same time, we found that the relative concentration of CA-CQDs in the produced fluid almost reached 100% after the cumulative injection reached 3 PV. This showed that CA-CQDs still had excellent stability at lower injection pressure. The evaluation experiment of the damage of CA-CQDs to the reservoir was presented in Table 7
                        . The permeability of the reservoir decreased slightly after the injection of CA-CQDs due to the small amount of adsorption of CA-CQDs during the migration process that changed the pore structure of the reservoir. Compared with the initial permeability, the damage rate of the reservoir was generally below 6%, which reflected weak damage and met the requirements for the on-site use of tracers.
